// Tri·∫øt standard library ‚Äî std.sys.atomic
//
// Atomic primitive per [ADR-0028]. Cross-thread shared-mutable
// wrapper for `AtomicValue` primitives (`Trit` / `Tryte` / `Integer` /
// `Trilean` / `Pointer`). `Long` excluded ‚Äî exceeds hardware atomic
// width on both 64-bit binary CPUs and forecast trytecode hardware
// (use `std.concurrency.Mutex` v0.10 or 3√ó `Atomic<Integer>` manually).
//
// All operations are Rust-shim builtins per ADR-0019 ¬ß5. VM dispatch
// lands at builtin IDs 33-42 (v0.9.x.atomic.2-4). Function bodies
// here are placeholders ‚Äî VM intercepts cross-module calls via
// `path_to_builtin` per ADR-0019 Addendum ¬ßA7.
//
// **Concurrency model:** VM is single-thread (dev tier per VISION
// ¬ß4.3) ‚Äî `Ordering` argument validated at typecheck but no-op at
// runtime. Real concurrency semantics land when AOT/JIT + OS threads
// arrive (v0.10+ stdlib).
//
// **Reference form:** all ops take `&+ Atomic<T>` (frozen owner) ‚Äî
// atomicity is internal interior mutability per ADR-0028 ¬ß5.
// Multi-thread share via refcount; race conditions resolved by
// `Ordering`, not Tri·∫øt's borrow checker.
//
// **Capability gate:** `sys.atomic` capability required per ADR-0028
// ¬ß8 ‚Äî declare `requires sys.atomic grant` in `dao.package`.
//
// **Parameter naming:** ADR-0028 signatures use `self` for the atomic
// receiver; this stdlib uses `atom` because `self` is reserved for
// import path qualification (`self.lexer`, ADR-0019 ¬ß3).

/// Memory ordering level per ADR-0028 ¬ß3. Trit polarity carries
/// strength:
///
/// - `Relaxed`     ‚Äî Trit::Negative (-1), weakest ‚Äî atomic only, no
///                   inter-thread synchronization. Use with care.
/// - `Synchronized` ‚Äî Trit::Zero    ( 0), middle ‚Äî acquire on load,
///                   release on store (C++ `memory_order_acq_rel`).
///                   **Default** for all ops without explicit ordering.
/// - `Strict`     ‚Äî Trit::Positive (+1), strongest ‚Äî total order across
///                   all threads (C++ `memory_order_seq_cst`).
public enum Ordering {
    Relaxed,
    Synchronized,
    Strict,
}

/// Compare-exchange failure payload per ADR-0028 ¬ß4.1. Carries the
/// actual current value seen when `expected` did NOT match ‚Äî caller
/// retries the CAS loop with the new value.
public struct CompareExchangeFailed<T> {
    actual: T,
}

/// Construct an `Atomic<T>` initialized to `initial_value`. Caller
/// stores ownership and borrows as `&+ counter` for cross-thread
/// share. Stack-allocated per ADR-0028 ¬ß6 ‚Äî no heap, no `ObjectHeader`.
public function new<T>(initial_value: T) -> Atomic<T> = new(initial_value)

/// Load value from atomic. `Ordering.Synchronized` is the safe default.
public function load<T>(atom: &+ Atomic<T>, ordering: Ordering) -> T = load(atom, ordering)

/// Store value into atomic. Atomicity is internal ‚Äî owner ref is `&+` frozen
/// per ADR-0028 ¬ß5 (interior mutability).
public function store<T>(atom: &+ Atomic<T>, value: T, ordering: Ordering) {}

/// Swap atomic with new value, return previous.
public function swap<T>(atom: &+ Atomic<T>, value: T, ordering: Ordering) -> T = swap(atom, value, ordering)

/// Compare-exchange. Returns `~+ previous_value` if `expected` matched
/// and was replaced; `~- CompareExchangeFailed { actual }` if not.
/// See ADR-0028 ¬ß4.1.
public function compare_exchange<T>(
    atom: &+ Atomic<T>,
    expected: T,
    new_value: T,
    success_ordering: Ordering,
    failure_ordering: Ordering,
) -> T~CompareExchangeFailed<T> = compare_exchange(atom, expected, new_value, success_ordering, failure_ordering)

/// Atomically add `delta`, return previous value (pre-modification).
/// `Atomic<Integer>` or `Atomic<Tryte>` per ADR-0028 ¬ß4.2.
public function fetch_add(atom: &+ Atomic<Integer>, delta: Integer, ordering: Ordering) -> Integer = fetch_add(atom, delta, ordering)

/// Atomically subtract `delta`, return previous value (pre-modification).
public function fetch_sub(atom: &+ Atomic<Integer>, delta: Integer, ordering: Ordering) -> Integer = fetch_sub(atom, delta, ordering)

/// Atomic bitwise AND. **Binary-semantic escape hatch** per ADR-0028
/// Addendum ¬ß4.3 ‚Äî operates on 64-bit binary slot, NOT Tri·∫øt's 27-trit
/// ternary value. Explicit `_bitwise_` prefix signals binary leak.
/// Use only for FFI scenarios where `Atomic<Integer>` stores a packed
/// binary value (kernel flag bytes, etc.).
public function fetch_bitwise_and(atom: &+ Atomic<Integer>, mask: Integer, ordering: Ordering) -> Integer = fetch_bitwise_and(atom, mask, ordering)

/// Atomic bitwise OR. Same binary-semantic warning as `fetch_bitwise_and`.
public function fetch_bitwise_or(atom: &+ Atomic<Integer>, mask: Integer, ordering: Ordering) -> Integer = fetch_bitwise_or(atom, mask, ordering)

/// Atomic bitwise XOR. Same binary-semantic warning as `fetch_bitwise_and`.
public function fetch_bitwise_xor(atom: &+ Atomic<Integer>, mask: Integer, ordering: Ordering) -> Integer = fetch_bitwise_xor(atom, mask, ordering)
